   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def make_title(data, start=None):\n",
    "    if start is None:\n",
    "        title = f\"{str(data.index.min().date())} to {str(data.index.max().date())}\"\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        title = (\n",
    "            f\"{start}: {str(data.index.min().date())} to {str(data.index.max().date())}\"\n",
    "        )\n",
    "    return title\n"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "EfTQ7gMErT9h"
   },
   "source": [
    "## Time series decomposition\n",
    "Time Series Decomposition is a technique to extract multiple types of variation from your dataset. There are three important components in the temporal data of a time series: seasonality, trend, and noise.\n",
    "\n",
    "Seasonality is a recurring movement that is present in your time series variable. For example, the temperature of a place will be higher in the summer months and lower in the winter months. You could compute average monthly temperatures and use this seasonality as a basis for forecasting future values.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "A trend can be a long-term upward or downward pattern. In a temperature time series, a trend could be present due to global warming. For example, on top of the summer/winter seasonality, you may well see a slight increase in average temperatures over time.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Noise is the part of the variability in a time series that can neither be explained by seasonality nor by a trend. When building models, you end up combining different components into a mathematical formula. Two parts of such a formula can be seasonality and trend. A model that combines both will never represent the values of temperature perfectly: an error will always remain. This is represented by the noise factor."
   ]
  },
  {

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Zw4OFN3hDSJb"
   },
   "source": [
    "### Trend\n",
    "The Dickey-Fuller test is a statistical hypothesis test that allows you to detect non-stationarity.\n",
    "\n",
    "The null hypothesis of the ADF test is that a unit root is present in the time series. The alternative hypothesis is that the data is stationary.\n",
    "\n",
    "If the p-value is smaller than 0.05 you can reject the null hypothesis (reject non-stationarity) and accept the alternative hypothesis (stationarity). In both cases, we can reject the null hypothesis and assume that the data are stationary. As you have seen with the seasonal decompose plots above, you know that there is an upward trend in both data, so this also confirms the result we obtained."
   ]
  },
  {

    "print('GSK ADF number of observations:', nobs)\n",
    "print('GSK ADF critical values:', crit_vals)\n",
    "print('GSK ADF best information criterion:', icbest)\n",
    "print(f'GSK Stationary? ==> {pval < 0.05}')"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "yyNXXW2vdud7"
   },
   "source": [
    "## Check for Autocorrelation\n",
    "\n",
    "A time series data is said to be autoregressive if a current value can be obtained by a previous value. Similarly a model is autoregressive if it predicts future values based on past values.\n",
    "\n",
    "ACF (auto-correlation function) describes how well the present value of the series is related with its past values\n",
    "\n",
    "PACF (partial auto-correlation function) describes how a present value of a series is related to a past value after removing the effects which are already explained by the earlier lag(s) with the next lag\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**Result:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Both data had very similar result.\n",
    "\n",
    "For ACF, they both had close to 1 correlation even past 50 lags\n",
    "\n",
    "For PACF, the close to 1 correlation ended at lag 1\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "my1t6cxbdzu0"
   },
   "source": [

   ]

   "source": [
    "# Reduce training data\n",
    "\n",
    "Since this is a short term forecast (daily), the more recent signals in the data is more valuable. As shown in the trend plots, the long term upward trend in the data may overshadow the more recent signals that is for a short term forecast\n",
    "\n",
    "The data used for modelling is from 2021-01-01 to 2023-07-19"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "DPzkOBnVmwkh"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "gsk_cl = gsk_cl.loc[\"2021\":]\n",
    "unilever_cl = unilever_cl.loc[\"2021\":]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Ko3ABgApZHgP"
   },
   "source": [
    "# Feature Engineering for ML models\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "uUcNRCLIg9IH"
   },
   "source": [
    " supervised models use dependent/target variables (the ones to predict) and independent variables (the predictors). supervised models cannot be built using only target variables. Feature engineering needs to be carried out to extract predictor variables from the data\n",
    "\n",
    " - since there is a high autocorrelation in both data, we'll use the values of the past 30 days as predictor variables for the 31st day\n",
    "\n",
    "- month is also extracted from the timeseries date to capture seasonality"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "nfHeqCZzl-qA"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def make_ml_data(data, n=30):\n",
    "    data_list = []\n",
    "    for sh in range(1,n+1):\n",
    "        data_list.append(data.shift(periods=sh, freq=freq))\n",
    "\n",
    "    new_data = pd.concat(data_list, axis=1)\n",
    "    new_data[\"month\"] = pd.DataFrame(data.index.month, index=data.index)\n",
    "    new_data = pd.concat([new_data, data], axis=1).dropna()\n",
    "    new_data.columns = [str(i) for i in list(range(1, n+1))] + [\"month\", \"y\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "    return new_data"
   ]
  },

    "gsk_ml = make_ml_data(gsk_cl, n=lag)\n",
    "ulvr_ml = make_ml_data(unilever_cl, n=lag)\n",
    "ulvr_ml.head(30)[-1::-1]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "fWe5lq3B2G9T"
   },
   "source": [
    "# Helper Functions and Variables\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "6mEQ5bMo2TL0"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def model_arima(data):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Return best ARIMA model (with its parameters). Modelling is done using\n",
    "    ndiffs to find best d parameter\n",
    "    pm.auto_arima to find best p & q parameter\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # get param d\n",
    "    kpss_diffs = ndiffs(data, alpha=0.05, test=\"kpss\", max_d=6)\n",
    "    adf_diffs = ndiffs(data, alpha=0.05, test=\"adf\", max_d=6)\n",
    "    n_diffs = max(adf_diffs, kpss_diffs)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # find best params (p, q) and model\n",
    "    best_model = pm.auto_arima(\n",
    "        data,\n",
    "        stepwise=True,\n",
    "        suppress_warnings=True,\n",
    "        trace=1,\n",
    "        random_state=seed,\n",
    "        out_of_sample_size=days,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    return best_model\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_forecasts(actual, pred, forecast_days, size=200, name=None):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Make timeseries plot of the actual data vs the forecasted\"\"\"\n",
    "    actual_pred = pd.concat([actual, pred], axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    actual_pred.columns = [\"actual\", \"forecast\"]\n",
    "    data = actual_pred.iloc[-size:].copy()\n",
    "    fig = sns.lineplot(data, linewidth=2)\n",
    "    plt.title(\n",
    "        f\"{name} forecast: {str(data.index.min().date())} to {str(data.index.max().date())}\"\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    return fig\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def model_prophet(data):\n",
    "    \"\"\"modelling for prophet model\"\"\"\n",
    "    ## preprocess data\n",
    "    new_data = data.reset_index()\n",
    "    new_data.columns = [\"ds\", \"y\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "    ## fit model\n",
    "    model = Prophet()\n",
    "    model.fit(new_data)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return model\n",
    "\n",
    "def t_split(data, size=14):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Split the data with the specified test size\n",
    "    Return the indices of the split for RandomizedSearchCV CV parameter\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    split = [\n",
    "        (\n",
    "            data.iloc[:-size].reset_index().index.values,\n",
    "            data.iloc[-size:].reset_index().index.values,\n",
    "        )\n",
    "    ]\n",
    "    return split\n",
    "\n",
    "def get_best_ml_model(model, X, y, grid, n_iter=30):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Return best ML model for the passed base model (XGB/RF)\n",
    "    after using RandomizedSearchCV to get best hyperparameter\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    best_ml_model = RandomizedSearchCV(\n",
    "        estimator=model,\n",
    "        param_distributions=grid,\n",
    "        n_iter=n_iter,\n",
    "        cv=t_split(X, days),\n",
    "        verbose=1,\n",
    "        random_state=0,\n",
    "        n_jobs=-1,\n",
    "        scoring=\"neg_mean_squared_error\",\n",
    "        return_train_score=True,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Fit the random search model\n",
    "    best_ml_model.fit(X.values, y.values)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return best_ml_model\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_all_forecats(data, title, size= 150):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Plots all given timeseries data\"\"\"\n",
    "    fig = sns.lineplot(data[-size:], dashes=False)\n",
    "    title = make_title(data, title)\n",
    "    plt.title(title)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return fig"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "KFSet1d0Rbkc"
   },
   "outputs": [],

    "\n",
    "\n",
    "forecasts = {\n",
    "    \"GSK\": {},\n",
    "    \"ULVR\": {},\n",
    "}   # to hold the forecasted data of the final models\n",
    "\n",
    "timings = {\n",
    "    \"ARIMA\": {\"GSK\": None, \"ULVR\": None},\n",
    "    \"prophet\": {\"GSK\": None, \"ULVR\": None},\n",
    "    \"RF\": {\"GSK\": None, \"ULVR\": None},\n",
    "    \"XGB\": {\"GSK\": None, \"ULVR\": None},\n",
    "}   # to hold the models' runtime\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "plots = {\n",
    "    \"ARIMA\": {\"GSK\": None, \"ULVR\": None},\n",
    "    \"prophet\": {\"GSK\": None, \"ULVR\": None},\n",
    "    \"RF\": {\"GSK\": None, \"ULVR\": None},\n",
    "    \"XGB\": {\"GSK\": None, \"ULVR\": None},\n",
    "}   # to hold the models' plots"
   ]

   "source": [
    "## Splitting\n",
    "\n",
    "40 days of data used as test data is seperated from each data (GSK, ULVR)\n",
    "\n",
    "No shuffling is done, and the last 40 days is the test data\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "2fGSYXTqSLXe"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "days = 40\n",
    "train_gsk, test_gsk = gsk_cl.iloc[:-days], gsk_cl.iloc[-days:]\n",
    "train_gsk, test_gsk = gsk_cl.iloc[:-days], gsk_cl.iloc[-days:]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "train_ulvr, test_ulvr = unilever_cl.iloc[:-days], unilever_cl.iloc[-days:]\n",
    "train_ulvr, test_ulvr = unilever_cl.iloc[:-days], unilever_cl.iloc[-days:]\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "LGDqlcKVnEPD"
   },
   "source": [
    "test data / held out data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "H9GYqwhqOrqZ"
   },
   "source": [
    "## ARIMA\n",
    "__PROCEDURE__\n",
    "\n",
    "- Hold out last 40 days of data for testing\n",
    "- Estimate differencing term, d on the remaining data using the ndiffs class in pmdarima library\n",
    "- make an ARIMA model with the best p and q using the autoarima class in pmdarima library\n",
    "- make a 40 day forecast to be tested with the test data\n",
    "- Calculate the MSE of the forescasted data to the test data\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "YAu7o2ms94h_"
   },

    "    test_gsk, pd.DataFrame(forecasts_[\"yhat\"][-days:].values, index=test_gsk.index)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "results[\"prophet\"][\"GSK\"][\"test\"] = {\n",
    "    \"MSE\": f\"{test_score:.2f}\",\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"MSE values\")\n",
    "pprint(results[\"prophet\"][\"GSK\"])\n"
   ]
  },

    "# ML Models"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "vjXaiUyVzE3l"
   },
   "source": [
    "## splitting\n",
    "\n",
    "splitting is same as for statistical model as 40 days of data is kept for testing\n",
    "\n",
    "For ml models, we also split each data into X and y i.e X_train, y_train. X_test, y_test"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 41,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "kSlcLwQOzD64"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "days = 40\n",
    "\n",
    "# cut out n samples for validation (holdout)\n",
    "train_gsk, hold_out_gsk = gsk_ml.iloc[:-days], gsk_ml.iloc[-days:]\n",
    "train_ulvr, hold_out_ulvr = ulvr_ml.iloc[:-days], ulvr_ml.iloc[-days:]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Split remaining to X, y\n",
    "X_gsk_ml, y_gsk_ml = train_gsk.iloc[:, :-1], train_gsk.iloc[:, -1]\n",
    "X_ulvr_ml, y_ulvr_ml = train_ulvr.iloc[:, :-1], train_ulvr.iloc[:, -1]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Split holdout to X, y\n",
    "X_hold_out_gsk, y_hold_out_gsk = hold_out_gsk.iloc[:, :-1], hold_out_gsk.iloc[:, -1]\n",
    "X_hold_out_ulvr, y_hold_out_ulvr = hold_out_ulvr.iloc[:, :-1], hold_out_ulvr.iloc[:, -1]\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Syvf47rVPckj"
   },
   "source": [
    "## Random Forest\n",
    "\n",
    "__PROCEDURE__\n",
    "\n",
    "- Hold out last 40 days of data for testing\n",
    "- using Randomized search cross validation, find the best hyperparameters for the model and model the data with it. The hyperparameters considered are\n",
    "\n",
    "    - n_estimators\n",
    "    - max_depth\n",
    "\n",
    "- make a 40 day forecast to be tested with the test data\n",
    "- Calculate the MSE of the forescasted data to the test data\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "KSAvTboPIsFd"
   },
   "source": [
    "### GSK"
   ]

    "\n",
    "# Number of features to consider at every split\n",
    "max_depth = [1, 2, 3, 4]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the random grid\n",
    "random_grid = {\n",
    "    \"n_estimators\": n_estimators,\n",
    "    \"max_depth\": max_depth,\n",
    "}\n",
    "[int(x) for x in np.linspace(3, 13, num=7)] + [None]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the random grid\n",
    "random_grid = {\n",
    "    \"n_estimators\": n_estimators,\n",
    "    \"max_depth\": max_depth,\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"grid\")\n",
    "pprint(random_grid)\n"
   ]

    "## XGBoost\n",
    "\n",
    "__PROCEDURE__\n",
    "\n",
    "- Hold out last 40 days of data for testing\n",
    "- using Randomized search cross validation, find the best hyperparameters for the model and model the data with it. The hyperparameters considered are\n",
    "\n",
    "    - n_estimators\n",
    "    - max_depth\n",
    "    - learning rate\n",
    "\n",
    "- make a 40 day forecast to be tested with the held out data\n",
    "- Calculate the MSE of the forescasted data to the held out data\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },

     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start=50, stop=500, num=10)]\n",
    "\n",

    "max_depth = [1, 2]\n",
    "learning_rate = [0.01, 0.1, 0.001]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the random grid\n",
    "random_grid = {\n",
    "    \"n_estimators\": n_estimators,\n",
    "    \"max_depth\": max_depth,\n",
    "    \"learning_rate\": learning_rate,\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n\\n\", \"grid\")\n",
    "print(random_grid)\n"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 51,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
    },
    "id": "72aS6whPH38A",
    "outputId": "5ee985d5-8c94-4979-d15b-4672ed970c93"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Fitting 1 folds for each of 20 candidates, totalling 20 fits\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "time 4.073266983032227 secs\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "start_time = time()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "xgb = XGBRegressor()\n",
    "xgb_random = get_best_ml_model(xgb, X_gsk_ml, y_gsk_ml, random_grid, 20)\n",
    "\n",
    "xgb_random.best_params_\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "end_time = time() - start_time\n",
    "print(\"\\n\\ntime\", end_time, \"secs\")\n",
    "\n",
    "timings[\"XGB\"][\"GSK\"] = end_time"
   ]

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 54,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

    "id": "t-ahgq1gOLqk",

   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "grid\n",
      "{'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.001],\n",
      " 'max_depth': [1, 2],\n",
      " 'n_estimators': [50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400, 450, 500]}\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "n_estimators =[int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 50, stop = 500, num = 10)]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Number of features to consider at every split\n",
    "max_depth =[1, 2,]\n",
    "\n",
    "learning_rate = [0.01, 0.1, 0.001]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the random grid\n",
    "random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,\n",
    "               'max_depth': max_depth,\n",
    "               'learning_rate': learning_rate\n",
    "              }\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n\\ngrid\")\n",
    "pprint(random_grid)"
   ]
